{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17412741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17412741"},"attributes":{"position":1,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261066"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261066"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1690"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500888"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:19:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:19:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1690"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261066"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:33:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:38:50+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":2,"questionsAnswered":1,"marksTotal":1,"marksAttainable":1,"marksAttempted":1,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T07:37:39+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"1690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1690"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.05,0.02,0.36,0.52]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1690"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56062"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1690"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1690"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41614"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1243"},{"type":"tags","id":"6132"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5243"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5247"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7015"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14444"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56062"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of pain in his right shoulder. His symptoms started after an afternoon spent installing ceiling lights. This is the first time he has experienced these symptoms. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is no apparent deformity or swelling in the shoulder region. There is tenderness over the subacromial bursa and weakness on shoulder abduction at the shoulder joint. External rotation is also limited.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acromioclavicular ligament tear","Subdeltoid bursitis","Teres major tendon tear","Supraspinatus tendon tear","Subacromial bursitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe symptoms presented in this case most closely fit with a rotator cuff injury, specifically a \u003Cstrong\u003Esupraspinatus tendon tear\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient has an identifiable trigger for his symptoms (installing ceiling lights), which involves overhead arm movements. Risk factors for rotator cuff injuries include age over 40 years and repetitive rotator cuff strain, such as repeated overhead movements over a long period. The clinical findings of weakness on shoulder abduction and limited external rotation strongly support the diagnosis of a supraspinatus tendon tear, as the supraspinatus is a key muscle in shoulder abduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eacromioclavicular ligament tear\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with pain at the top of the shoulder and a visible deformity or step-off at the acromioclavicular joint, usually following direct trauma to the shoulder. This patient\u0027s presentation lacks any mention of trauma or visible deformity, making this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubdeltoid bursitis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause shoulder pain, but it typically presents with pain on abduction between 60 and 120 degrees (painful arc syndrome). While there might be some weakness due to pain, the specific weakness on abduction noted in this case is more indicative of a rotator cuff tear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eteres major tendon tear\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare injury that would primarily affect shoulder adduction and internal rotation, rather than abduction and external rotation as seen in this case. The teres major is not part of the rotator cuff and is less commonly injured in overhead activities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubacromial bursitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a reasonable differential for this presentation. It can cause pain and limitation of movement, especially with overhead activities. However, true weakness on abduction is more characteristic of a rotator cuff tear than bursitis alone. In bursitis, patients are often reluctant to perform a full range of movement due to pain, which can be misinterpreted as weakness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the combination of the patient\u0027s age, the mechanism of injury (overhead activity), tenderness over the subacromial bursa, weakness on abduction, and limited external rotation are most consistent with a supraspinatus tendon tear. While other conditions may share some features, the overall clinical picture strongly supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Rotator cuff injury most commonly presents with painful abduction and external rotation of the shoulder.","Rotator cuff injuries are more common in individuals over 40 years old and those who perform repetitive overhead movements.","Weakness on shoulder abduction is a key clinical sign of a rotator cuff tear."],"references":["Stevenson JH, Trojian T. Evaluation of shoulder pain. Journal of family practice. 2002 Jul 1;51(7):605-11. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12160496/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41614"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1690"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41614"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-19T11:20:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-19T11:22:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1690"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56062"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt"